text=%Pm% [[!Documentation ToDo]] -- The newer portions at the foot of this page need to be rewritten in a more "tutorial" style rather than a simple list of examples.  --[[~Pm]]²----²²%define=mystyle font-family:monospace%²!!! Image inline in page²Key the full address of the image file²(:markup:) [=http://www.pmwiki.org/pmwiki/pub/skins/pmwiki/pmwiki-32.gif=]²NOTES: ²*This works for images on another site as well as for images on your own, '''''but''''' it is considered ''very bad manners'' to link directly in this way to an image on another site.  The example here is an exception, made by the author of the PmWiki wiki-engine for illustration purposes.²*To limit the size of the image as it is displayed, preface the link with scaling or size-restriction markup - e.g. [=%width=100% or %height=200%=].  Experiment with the number of pixels specified to get the image size that you want.²%color=violet% A nice feature would be to be able to set the resizing as a percentage of the page width instead of pixels (as it is already for tables). This would allow to display multiple images on a same line independently of the screen resolution. [[~jmi]] May 28, 2005, at 05:40 PM²----²!!! Image centered using table²(:markup:) [=²||align='center'²||http://www.pmwiki.org/pmwiki/pub/skins/pmwiki/pmwiki-32.gif||²=]²or²(:markup:)[=|| http://www.pmwiki.org/pmwiki/pub/skins/pmwiki/pmwiki-32.gif ||=]²or² %mystyle%[=² (:table width=200%:)² (:cell align=center:)² http://www.pmwiki.org/pmwiki/pub/skins/pmwiki/pmwiki-32.gif² (:tableend:)²=]²(:table width=200%:)²(:cell align=center:)²http://www.pmwiki.org/pmwiki/pub/skins/pmwiki/pmwiki-32.gif²(:tableend:)²----²!!! Link to image²In the first example (above), we saw that simply keying the image's full address causes the image to be shown.  ²²How then do we ''prevent'' the address from being rendered as an image, if we want to provide ''the address'' of the image?²²Put double square brackets around the address.²(:markup:) [=[[http://www.pmwiki.org/pmwiki/pub/skins/pmwiki/pmwiki-32.gif]]=]²----²!!! Image linking to image²Use the image as a clickable link - linking to the image itself, or to a different image.  Use the [=[[Go | Show]]=] convention: the first half is a link to the image file (or to any other linkable location); the second half is what will be displayed.²(:markup:) [=[[http://www.pmichaud.com/img/wiki/pmichaud.com-40.gif | http://www.pmwiki.org/pmwiki/pub/skins/pmwiki/pmwiki-32.gif]]=]²----²!!! Image as thumbnail linking to full-sized image²To display a Thumbnail version of an image, which when clicked opens the full image onscreen, ²*Use the image as a clickable link - linking to the image itself.  Use the [=[[Go | Show]]=] convention: the first half is a link to the image file; the second half is what will be displayed.²*Preface the link's opening pair of double square brackets with scaling or size restriction markup - e.g. [=%width=100% or %height=200%=].  Experiment with the number of pixels specified to get the thumbnail size that you want.²(:markup:) [=%width=50%[[http://www.pmichaud.com/grape/in-grape2.gif | http://www.pmichaud.com/grape/in-grape2.gif ]]=]²----²!!! Image linking to link²Use the image as a clickable link - linking to another location. Use the [=[[Go | Show]]=] convention - the first half is a link to the other linkable location; the second half is what will be displayed.²(:markup:) [=[[http://www.pmichaud.com | http://www.pmichaud.com/img/wiki/pmichaud.com-40.gif]]=]²----²!!! Image scaled²(:markup:) [=%define=scaled width:120%²%scaled% http://www.pmwiki.org/pmwiki/pub/skins/pmwiki/pmwiki-32.gif=]²----²!!! Float right image²(:markup:) [=%align=right%http://www.pmichaud.com/grape/in-grape2.gif [[<<]]=]²----²!!! Float right image followed by text²(:markup:) [=%align=right%http://www.pmwiki.org/pmwiki/pub/skins/pmwiki/pmwiki-32.gif [[<<]] The text should follow the image with a line break between the text and the image=]²----²!!! Floating image with text wrapping around it[[#floatwrap]]²You can include an image near some text and have the text wrap around the image with a bit of open space between the image and the text.  Adjust the ''hspace'' and ''vspace'' values to suit your own taste.²²(:markup:)²%align=left hspace=8 vspace=2% http://www.pmwiki.org/pmwiki/pub/skins/pmwiki/pmwiki-32.gif%%²Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetuer adipiscing elit. Donec vitae purus non mauris dapibus congue. Nulla facilisi. Curabitur non quam. Vivamus sem orci, euismod sed, faucibus vitae, tristique vel, orci. Donec elementum. Curabitur id dui. Aenean imperdiet, arcu in pulvinar luctus, sapien eros pulvinar elit, vel mattis felis dolor ut nunc. Ut viverra. Sed scelerisque vulputate pede. Duis elit purus, porttitor quis, accumsan ac, tincidunt luctus, pede.(:markupend:)²²(:markup:)²%align=right hspace=8 vspace=2% http://www.pmwiki.org/pmwiki/pub/skins/pmwiki/pmwiki-32.gif%%²Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetuer adipiscing elit. Donec vitae purus non mauris dapibus congue. Nulla facilisi. Curabitur non quam. Vivamus sem orci, euismod sed, faucibus vitae, tristique vel, orci. Donec elementum. Curabitur id dui. Aenean imperdiet, arcu in pulvinar luctus, sapien eros pulvinar elit, vel mattis felis dolor ut nunc. Ut viverra. Sed scelerisque vulputate pede. Duis elit purus, porttitor quis, accumsan ac, tincidunt luctus, pede.(:markupend:)²----²!!! Image with alt tag²(:markup:) [=http://www.pmwiki.org/pmwiki/pub/skins/pmwiki/pmwiki-32.gif"PmWiki is built with PHP"=]²----²About '''alt''' tag, it might be interesting to also populate the '''title''' [[~Isidor]]²²It would be ''good'' to populate the title, since Firefox doesn't normally show the alt text, in recognition that the purpose of the alt tag is to provide text when an image fails to render, where-as the '''title''' is intended to provide the "tool-tip" that many users expect from an '''alt''' tag.  Discussion [[http://www.webdeveloper.com/forum/showthread.php?t=62602 | here]]. ²----²!!! Image with spacing²(:markup:) [=²%vspace=30 hspace=30% http://www.pmwiki.org/pmwiki/pub/skins/pmwiki/pmwiki-32.gif=]²----²!!! Discussion²Why not use [@(:markup:) [=...=]@] directive for all the above?? - [[~Klonk]]²: :doesn't work for @@(: ... :)@@²²----²Is it possible to specify a padding or margin for the image?²²||align=left  cellpadding=10px²|| http://www.pmichaud.com/grape/in-grape2.gif || ²At the moment (pmwiki2 beta26) it is not possible to specify padding for images directly. It could be done in the css style sheet. the image to the left is wrapped in a table with cellpadding=10px[[<<]]²----²Is it possible to specify an uploaded image (Attachment) to be displayed inline? Can I use [=[[go|Attach:OtherGroup/Image.gif]]=] ?²²Answer: '''''you can now!'''''  It will depend on your version of PmWiki.  If it doesn't work for your version, then just use the image's full url, as if it were on another site, e.g. (for a site with "clean urls") [=http://www.sitename.com/uploads/Main/Image.gif=]²----²(:markup:)[=%align=left height=80 margin=4em%http://www.pmichaud.com/grape/in-grape2.gif Text to be associated with first image [[<<]]=]²²(:markup:)[=%align=left height=80%http://www.pmichaud.com/grape/in-grape2.gif Text to be associated with second image [[<<]]=]²²How to display an image that does not have an image extension (like .gif). I have this case because I would like to display a page counter which is generated, and it has a .dat file extension. (the same with .php images?)²²Thanks²²->%Pm% Add a "false" extension to the URL.  For example, if the url is [=http://www.example.com/cgi-bin/counter.php=], just add a fake query string on the end with the desired extension (e.g., [=http://www.example.com/cgi-bin/counter.php?dummy=.gif=]) and PmWiki will assume it's a .gif.  --[[~Pm]]²²²²²%trail%<<|[[PmWiki.Documentation Index]]|>>²²Categories: [[!Images]], [[!Layout]]
